    <h2>Introduction to Plant Pathology</h2>

    <p>
      Plant pathology is the study of plant diseases, their causes,
      development, spread, diagnosis, and control. Plant diseases
      reduce crop yield, quality, and farmer income.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Study of plant diseases</li>
        <li>Study of pathogens</li>
        <li>Disease prevention and control</li>
        <li>Protection of food production</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Concept of Plant Disease</h2>

    <p>
      Plant disease is an abnormal condition that interferes with
      normal plant growth and function.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Infectious diseases</strong> – caused by pathogens</li>
      <li><strong>Non-infectious diseases</strong> – caused by environmental factors</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Plant Disease Diagnosis</h2>

    <p>
      Diagnosis involves identifying diseases using symptoms,
      signs, and pathogen structures.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <strong>Common Symptoms:</strong>
      Mosaic, chlorosis, wilting, blight, canker, rot, stunting.
    </div>

    <h2>Non-Parasitic Diseases</h2>

    <p>
      Caused by environmental or abiotic factors.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>High or low temperature</li>
      <li>Nutrient deficiency</li>
      <li>Air pollution</li>
      <li>Improper moisture</li>
      <li>Pesticide injury</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Parasitic or Biotic Agents</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Viruses</li>
      <li>Viroids</li>
      <li>Bacteria</li>
      <li>Mollicutes</li>
      <li>Protists</li>
      <li>Nematodes</li>
      <li>Fungi</li>
      <li>Parasitic plants</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Disease Cycle</h2>

    <p>
      The disease cycle is the sequence of events in disease
      development.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      Dissemination → Inoculation → Penetration → Infection →
      Colonization → Symptom Development → Survival
    </div>

    <h2>Variability in Plant Pathogens</h2>

    <p>
      Pathogens change genetically through mutation,
      hybridization, recombination, and reproduction.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Mutation</li>
      <li>Transformation</li>
      <li>Conjugation</li>
      <li>Sexual reproduction</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Mechanisms of Pathogenicity</h2>

    <p>
      Pathogens damage plants by interfering with normal
      physiological processes.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Interference with water uptake</li>
      <li>Reduced photosynthesis</li>
      <li>Increased transpiration</li>
      <li>Cell and tissue death</li>
      <li>Toxin and enzyme production</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Mechanisms of Disease Resistance</h2>

    <p>
      Resistance is the ability of plants to suppress
      pathogen growth.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Pre-formed resistance</li>
      <li>Induced resistance</li>
      <li>Hypersensitive reaction</li>
      <li>Phytoalexin production</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Epidemiology of Plant Disease</h2>

    <p>
      Epidemiology studies the development and spread
      of plant diseases in populations.
    </p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <strong>Elements of an Epidemic:</strong>
      Susceptible host, virulent pathogen,
      favorable environment, and human activities.
    </div>

    <h2>Principles of Plant Disease Control</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Exclusion</strong> – prevent entry of pathogen</li>
      <li><strong>Eradication</strong> – eliminate pathogen</li>
      <li><strong>Protection</strong> – protect host from infection</li>
      <li><strong>Resistance</strong> – use resistant varieties</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Methods of Disease Control</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Quarantine</li>
      <li>Sanitation</li>
      <li>Crop rotation</li>
      <li>Biological control</li>
      <li>Chemical control</li>
      <li>Use of resistant cultivars</li>
      <li>Use of disease-free planting materials</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="info-box">
      <strong>Key Integration:</strong><br><br>
      Plant disease develops through the interaction
      of the host, pathogen, and environment.
      Understanding pathogens, disease cycles,
      epidemiology, resistance, and disease control
      is essential in crop protection and sustainable agriculture.
    </div>

